When I worked in public libraries, I loved it. I loved wearing multiple hats and helping people, going beyond just doing reference work. But when you don't even consult with library workers about post-pandemic opening and then complain --- get out of here.
Invest in more cooling centers, more programs to care for your people during this unseasonably warm weather, so that you aren't relying 100% on ONE LIBRARY to be the public center of all things.

If they are saying they have legit concerns, listen to them. Why do you think they might be scared about fully reopening? Talk to your workers. Find out what a public library looks like at full capacity.

Librarians aren't just napping around in pristine air-conditioned book fortresses. They are social workers, literal life-savers (SPL trained its workers in NARCAN training), program coordinators, babysitters, teachers, the list goes on.
Job shadow a ref librarian or children's librarian for a week and then get back to me.
